Pascal, and Pascal-derived languages such as Modula and Turbo Pascal, have this:<p><pre><code>    type Age = 1..199;
</code></pre>
A value of type Age can only have the values 1 <= x <= 199, and can&#x27;t be assigned to non-Age variables. Enums belong to this category of ordinal types.<p>In Ada:<p><pre><code>    type Age is Range 1 .. 199;
    type Temperature is new Integer Range 32 .. 212;

    a: Age; t: Temperature
    a := t  -- this fails at compile time
</code></pre>
Ada 2012 adds the support for specifying Eiffel-style contracts, but on types:<p><pre><code>    subtype Even is Integer
      with Dynamic_Predicate => Even mod 2 = 0;
</code></pre>
You can&#x27;t assign an odd number to a variable of type Even.
